chances after, say,} Nf5 19. b3 b4 {.}) 18... Qb6 19. Bh4 $1 Kd7 {QUESTION:
What is this madness? ANSWER: It is not so mad. In fact this a typical idea in
the French Defence, which the game now resembles; the king is usually quite
safe on d7 and meanwhile the black rooks are connected. All the same, the
position is more difficult for Black than he perhaps anticipated.} 20. Ne3 ({
White might also consider} 20. Bf6 $5 {.} {But if Black defends the bishop
with a rook, White ties him down further with Ng5 and can then consider play
on both sides of the board; e.g.} Rag8 ({Taking the bishop is not an option:} 
20... Bxf6 $2 21. exf6 Nc8 ({while after} 21... Ng8 22. g5 {, the g8-knight
and h8-rook are shut out of the game}) 22. f5 $1 {breaks in quickly.}) 21. Ng5
Ke8 ({or} 21... Nd8 22. b3) 22. Ne3 Bc8 23. b3 {and so forth.}) 20... hxg4 21.
hxg4 Bh6 {Trying to disrupt White's kingside initiative by attacking the
f4-pawn.} 22. Ng5 {With a similar idea to that mentioned above: White puts
pressure on the pawns on the kingside pawns to force Black to adopt a purely
defensive and passive posture.} ({Inserting an exchange of bishops with} 22.
Bg5 Bxg5 23. Nxg5 Raf8 {looks to ease Black's defence;}) ({but} 22. Bf6 $5 Rh7
23. Rab1 {is another option, with various ideas of Ng5, b2-b3, or Kf2-g3 and
Rh1. Note that} Bxf4 $2 {runs into} 24. Nxc4 $1 dxc4 25. Qxf4 Nd5 26. Qg3 {
and White is clearly better.}) 22... Raf8 23. Rf1 Nd8 24. Rf3 {White has
plenty of time to improve his position, whereas it is difficult for Black to
make useful moves. The thrust ...b5-b4 doesn't help Black at all, given that
most of his pieces are tied up elsewhere.} ({Indeed, White might do well to
open the queenside himself with} 24. b3 {and so on.}) 24... Bg7 25. Qf2 f5 $5 {
QUESTION: I don't understand this move. Wasn't Black supposed to play on the
queenside? ANSWER: He was, but apparently he felt that White is making so much
progress on the kingside that Black needs to take active countermeasures there.
QUESTION: To whose advantage is such a change in the position? ANSWER: In
general, it has to be White who benefits the most, since his pieces are better
placed, while the e5-square and black pawn on e6 become permanent weaknesses.
On the other hand, if Black does nothing, White will just continue to build up
until his initiative becomes overwhelming. In that sense, Black's move is a
risk worth taking, and it pays off to the extent that White fails to find the
strongest continuation.} 26. exf6 Bxf6 27. Rh3 $6 ({White continues to take
his time, shuffling the pieces around, thus overlooking a much more aggressive
option that addresses the issue of Black's king being present in the centre:} 
27. f5 $1 gxf5 (27... exf5 28. gxf5 Rfg8 29. fxg6 Rxg6 30. Nh7 $1 {is very
strong too}) 28. gxf5 exf5 29. Re1 $1 {and White has a near decisive
initiative thanks to his perfectly coordinated pieces; e.g.} Kc8 30. Nxf5 Ng6
31. Bg3 $1 Bxg5 32. Nd6+ Kd7 33. Qe2 Kc6 34. Qe4 {with such threats as 34 Rxf8
Rxf8 35 Qg4+ Kc6 36 Bxd5+! Kxd5 37 Qe4 mate.}) 27... Qd6 28. Rf1 Bc8 29. Nf3 {
Exchanging dark-squared bishops enhances White's control over the e5-square.}
Bxh4 30. Rxh4 Kc7 ({The pawn on f4 is taboo:} 30... Qxf4 $4 31. Rxh8 Rxh8 32.
Ne5+ {wins the queen.}) 31. Ne5 $6 {It was better to exchange rooks on h8
first. The text move gives Black a chance to stir the pot.} Bd7 $6 {This is
just too passive.} ({Black should have tried} 31... Rxf4 $5 32. Rxh8 Rxf2 33.
Rxf2 Ndc6 {, even if the rooks are a bit better than the queen in this
position.}) 32. Qg3 ({Another idea is} 32. g5 $5 {, followed by N3g4-f6, with
good chances.}) 32... Be8 33. Qh2 Rxh4 34. Qxh4 {Now Black is condemned to a
passive defence again.} Nec6 35. Rf2 Qe7 36. Qh6 $6 {Exchanging queens would
only ease Black's defensive burden, who can finally look to generate
counterchances with ...b5-b4. When you have the initiative it is natural to go
forwards, but the text seems to be a mistake.} ({Instead, my computer suggests
the backwards move} 36. Qg3 $1 {, when the opposition of white queen and black
king on the h2-b8 diagonal is soon to be revealed by f4-f5. For example,} Nxe5
{(moving the king doesn't help, as White just plays 37 f5 anyway)} 37. f5 $1
gxf5 38. gxf5 Bc6 39. fxe6 Nxe6 40. Qxe5+ Qd6 41. Nxd5+ Bxd5 42. Rxf8 Nxf8 43.
Qxd5 Qxd5 44. Bxd5 {and Black faces a difficult defence a pawn down in the
endgame.}) 36... Nxe5 37. dxe5 ({Or if} 37. fxe5 {, then} Rxf2 38. Kxf2 Kc8 {
is perfectly playable for Black, having avoided the trick} 39. Bxd5 $1 {.})
37... Qc5 38. Nc2 Nc6 39. Nd4 $1 Nxd4 40. cxd4 Qe7 {On the last move before
the time control, realizing he can't take the d-pawn, Black cautiously
retreats.} ({It is probably too much to expect him to see the active idea of} 
40... Qb4 {and 41...Rf7!, which seems to draw more easily; e.g.} 41. f5 ({
or similarly} 41. Rf1 Rf7 $1 42. Qxg6 Qd2 43. Qxe6 Qe3+ 44. Rf2 Rxf4 {and
White has to take perpetual check}) 41... Rf7 $1 42. fxe6 ({or} 42. Re2 c3 $1)
42... Qe1+ 43. Rf1 Rxf1+ 44. Bxf1 Qg3+ {and so on.}) 41. a3 ({After} 41. f5
gxf5 42. gxf5 Rxf5 43. Rxf5 exf5 44. Bxd5 Qd7 $1 45. Qe6 Qd8 46. Kf1 b4 $1 47.
Bf3 ({or} 47. Bxc4 Qxd4) 47... Bb5 {, White's king is too exposed for him to
have serious winning chances.}) 41... Rf7 $6 {With the idea of ...Rh7, but
this is easily answered.} ({Instead, Black should at last play} 41... b4 $5 {
with counterplay.}) 42. f5 $1 gxf5 43. gxf5 Bd7 $6 {Another passive move.} ({
Black should have played as before} 43... Rxf5 44. Rxf5 exf5 45. Bxd5 Qd7 {
, though White's little extra move a2-a3 complicates things somewhat; e.g.} 46.
Qe6 Qd8 47. Kf1 b4 48. Bf3 Bb5 49. a4 $1 Qd7 50. Qg8 {and Black has to be very
careful.}) 44. f6 Qf8 45. Qg6 Qe8 46. Bh3 b4 {Better late than never, I
suppose.} 47. axb4 axb4 48. Bg4 $1 Kb6 49. Bh5 $6 {After this Black can set up
a blockade of sorts.} (49. Rh2 $1 {is a stronger plan, intending a timely Rh7;
for example,} Rf8 50. Qxe8 Rxe8 51. Rh7 c3 52. bxc3 b3 ({or} 52... bxc3 53. Bd1
) 53. Bh5 b2 54. Bg6 Rg8 55. Rg7 {and so forth.}) 49... Rf8 50. f7 Qc8 $4 {
