1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 ({Another Najdorf player, another game that began} 2... d6
{and then followed the previous one with} 3. g3 g6 4. d3 Bg7 5. Bg2 Nc6 {
and so on.}) 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e5 7. Qd2 Nge7 8. Bh6 O-O 9.
h4 $5 {By playing this before taking on g7, White rules out the blocking move .
..h7-h5. The drawback is that Black can exchange the bishops on h6 after all.}
f6 {QUESTION: This seems a little strange; what's the point? ANSWER: You
should be familiar with the point by now. Black intends to meet 10 h5?? with
10...Bxh6 11 Qxh6 g5, followed by 12...Kh8 and 13...Ng8, trapping the white
queen.} ({Nevertheless, Black can (and should) improve on this idea by trading
bishops first:} 9... Bxh6 $1 10. Qxh6 f6 ({not yet} 10... Nd4 $4 {which loses
on the spot to} 11. h5 $1 {etc}) 11. Qd2 {(White cannot make progress without
retreating the queen at some stage)} ({still not} 11. h5 $4 g5) ({while} 11.
O-O-O Nd4 12. f4 $4 Nef5 {is another trick to be avoided – but then White is
one or two tempi down on the main game}) 11... Nd4 ({or} 11... Kh8 $5 12. h5 g5
13. h6 Bg4 14. Nd1 Be6 15. f4 gxf4 16. gxf4 exf4 17. Nh3 Ng6 18. Nxf4 Nxf4 19.
Qxf4 f5 {and Black is well ahead in development, G.Knol-J.Van der Wiel,
Hoogeveen 2011}) 12. h5 (12. Nd1 f5 $5 13. c3 Ne6 14. exf5 gxf5 15. Ne3 f4 16.
Nd5 Kh8 17. Nxe7 Qxe7 {with a complicated position, where I personally prefer
Black's chances, M.Strijbos-J.Van der Wiel, Vlissingen 1998.} (17... Z0)) (12.
Nce2 d5 13. c3 Ndc6 14. f4 ({after} 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nf3 Bf5 16. O-O Qd7 17.
a3 Rad8 18. Rad1 a5 19. d4 cxd4 20. cxd4 e4 {, Black is already in charge of
the game, A.Orlov-R.Tischbierek, Porto San Giorgio 2003}) 14... Bg4 15. Bf3 Qd7
16. h5 gxh5 17. O-O-O dxe4 $6 (17... Rad8 {looks stronger}) 18. dxe4 Qxd2+ 19.
Rxd2 Rad8 20. Bxg4 hxg4 21. Rh4 exf4 {, and a draw was agreed in A.Krapivin-Mi.
Hoffmann, Moscow 2006, although there is still plenty left to play for.}) 12...
g5 13. h6 {(this reaches the same position as after 12...Kg8 in the game, but
with ...Nd4 thrown in for free and Black to move as well; surprisingly, this
is still playable for White)} Qa5 14. f4 exf4 (14... Bg4 $5 15. fxg5 f5 {
might be considered}) 15. gxf4 Ng6 16. f5 Ne5 17. O-O-O Bd7 18. Nge2 Bc6 19.
Kb1 Nxe2 ({or} 19... Nxf5 20. Bh3 {with compensation}) 20. Qxe2 b5 21. d4 cxd4
$6 (21... Nc4 {is preferable}) 22. Rxd4 {looks like an Open Sicilian where a
number of things have gone wrong for Black, E.Moser-I.Rajlich, European
Women's Team Championship, Plovdiv 2003.}) 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. h5 ({Anything
else and Black could just play 11...h5 again: a)} 11. f4 h5 12. Nd1 ({or} 12.
Bh3 Nd4 13. Nd1 Bxh3 14. Rxh3 Qd7 15. Nf2 Qa4 16. b3 Qa3 {and Black is clearly
better, K.Hönnekes-Ja.Becker, Bad Wiessee 1999}) 12... d5 13. Nf2 dxe4 14. Nxe4
exf4 15. gxf4 Bg4 16. Bf3 Qd5 17. c4 Qf5 18. O-O-O b6 19. Bxg4 Qxg4 20. Ne2
Rad8 21. Rhg1 Qxh4 22. f5 Nxf5 23. Nf4 Ne5 24. Ne6+ Kf7 25. Nxd8+ Rxd8 26. Qe2
Nd4 27. Qe3 Qf4 {and White resigned in M.Strijbos-Kr.Georgiev, Avoine 1995,
since after} 28. Qxf4 Ne2+ 29. Kc2 Nxf4 {, Black soon-to-be three connected
passed pawns are much stronger than White's extra exchange.}) ({b} 11. O-O-O {
Another option for Black is to play ...h7-h6, ruling out ideas of h4-h5-h6,
though this is more risky in that it allows White to push the f- and g-pawns.
For example,} h6 $5 (11... h5 12. f4 Bg4 (12... Nd4) (12... Qa5) ({and} 12...
Rb8 $5 {by ...b7-b5 are all logical too}) 13. Bf3 f5 14. Rf1 Nd4 15. Bxg4 fxg4
16. Nge2 Nf3 17. Qe3 Nc6 18. fxe5 Ncxe5 19. Nf4 Qe8 20. Kb1 b5 21. Ncd5 Rf7 {
and Black is certainly not worse, V.Bachin-M.Solovchuk, Vladivostok 2007.}) 12.
f4 Nd4 13. Rf1 Be6 14. Bh3 Bf7 15. g4 Nec6 16. g5 fxg5 17. hxg5 h5 18. Nf3 Qa5
19. f5 Bxa2 20. f6+ Kf7 {was A.Maljush-A.Zhigalko, Minsk 2006, and now} 21. Qg2
$1 {is the correct move, when the analysis becomes very interesting:} Nb4 $5 ({
Black can force a draw with} 21... Bb3 22. cxb3 Qa1+ 23. Nb1 Nxb3+ 24. Kc2
Ncd4+ 25. Nxd4 Nxd4+ 26. Kc1 Nb3+ {etc}) 22. Bf5 gxf5 (22... Rg8 {is met by
the brutal} 23. Qh2 $1 {intending} Nxf3 24. Bxg6+ $1 Rxg6 25. Qxh5 Nxg5 26.
Rhg1 {and wins}) 23. g6+ Ke8 ({not} 23... Kxf6 $2 24. exf5 Nxf3 25. Qxf3 Bb3 {
due to} 26. Rxh5 Qa1+ 27. Kd2 Qxb2 28. Qe4 $1 Qxc2+ 29. Ke3 Qxd3+ 30. Qxd3 Nxd3
31. Ne4+ $1 Ke7 32. Rh7+ Kd8 33. Kxd3 {and the two white pawns are very strong}
) 24. exf5 Rxf6 25. Ne4 Ndxc2 ({again not} 25... Bb3 $2 26. Nxd4 Nxd3+ 27. Kd1
Nxb2+ 28. Ke2 Bc4+ 29. Kf2 {and White is winning}) 26. Nxf6+ Kd8 27. Qg5 Bb3
28. Kd2 Kc7 29. Ke2 Qa6 {and the chaos continues. I apologize for giving this
long line, but it is a ton of fun.}) 11... g5 12. h6+ {QUESTION: Why this
move? Doesn't the pawn just get left to its own devices on h6, out of touch
with the remaining white army? ANSWER: The point is that it prevents Black
from sealing the kingside with ...h7-h6. Furthermore, the pawn can easily
become a thorn in Black's side, participating in White's attack, as we will
see in this game.} ({In any case, White has little hope of accomplishing
anything if he allows ...h7-h6. For example,} 12. f4 h6 13. Bh3 ({not} 13. Nh3
Nd4 14. fxg5 $6 fxg5 15. Nxg5 $2 Nec6 $1 16. Nh3 Bxh3 17. Rxh3 Qg5 $1 18. O-O-O
Rf2 {and Black is winning}) 13... Nd4 14. O-O-O b5 15. Nce2 Nec6 ({or} 15... d5
$5) 16. c3 (16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. Kb1 a5 {looks pleasant enough for Black}) 16...
Nxe2+ 17. Nxe2 d5 18. d4 $6 Bxh3 19. Rxh3 cxd4 20. exd5 Qxd5 {and Black has a
clear advantage, A.Pakhomov-R.Swinkels, Teplice 2009.}) 12... Kg8 $6 ({Tucking
the king in the corner with} 12... Kh8 $5 {is better, although here too White
gets his hands on the initiative:} 13. O-O-O (13. f4 $5 {, as in the main game,
is also an option}) 13... Ng6 14. Nge2 ({or} 14. Nd5 $5) 14... Nd4 15. Rdf1 (
15. Kb1 Bg4 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. Ne2 Rc8 18. f3 Be6 19. Bh3 Bxh3 20. Rxh3 d5 {
is double-edged}) 15... Qa5 16. a3 Nxe2+ 17. Nxe2 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 {with a tiny
plus for White in the queenless middlegame, F.La Rota-J.Smejkal, New York Open
1988.}) 13. f4 $1 {The vulnerability of Black's king on the g-file now becomes
apparent.} exf4 ({Black can consider the pawn sacrifice} 13... Bg4 14. fxg5 Nd4
{, but White should be better after} 15. Nd1 Bxd1 16. Rxd1 {.}) 14. gxf4 Ng6
15. Nge2 Bg4 $6 {Black's problems start to increase.} ({He should have played} 
15... Nd4 {, when} 16. f5 Nxe2 17. Nxe2 Ne5 18. O-O-O {definitely is more
promising for White, who will break with d3-d4, but it is much safer for Black
than the game continuation.}) 16. Bh3 $1 Bf3 17. Rg1 Nd4 $2 {The downhill ride
gains pace.} ({Here Black should have tried} 17... Kh8 18. O-O-O Nd4 19. Rdf1
Nxe2+ 20. Nxe2 Bxe2 21. Qxe2 Qe7 {, when he can still fight;} ({but not} 21...
Nxf4 $4 22. Rxf4 gxf4 23. Qg4 {, since 24 Qg7+! wins against every move.})) 18.
Nxd4 cxd4 19. Nd5 f5 $2 {Another mistake;} ({but even after} 19... Kh8 20. Rg3
Bh5 21. fxg5 fxg5 22. Qxg5 {, White should win rather easily.}) 20. Rxg5 fxe4
21. Be6+ Kh8 22. dxe4 Ne5 23. Qxd4 Rxf4 24. Rxe5 Qh4+ 25. Kd2 Qh2+ 26. Kc3 {
. With mate or heavy material losses around the corner, Black called it a day.}
1-0

