1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Rb8 7. a4 {Setting up
a temporary roadblock on the queenside, or if Black insists with ...a7-a6 and .
..b7-b5, as usually occurs, then the exchange of pawns on b5 opens the a-file
for White's rook. Strangely, in this game Black never gets round to pushing
the b-pawn.} ({The main move here is} 7. Qd2 {, which is considered in the
rest of this chapter;}) ({while} 7. f4 b5 8. Qd2 {is another path to Game 14.})
({In general,} 7. Nge2 {will transpose as well (to Games 16 or 17) if both Qd2
and ...b7-b5 are played, though this is not always the case. For example:} Nd4
(7... b5 8. a3 $5 Nf6 9. h3 O-O 10. b4 Nd7 11. Rb1 ({or} 11. O-O Nd4) 11...
cxb4 12. axb4 a5 13. bxa5 Qxa5 14. Bd2 (14. d4 b4 15. Ra1 Qd8 16. Nb1 Bb7 {
is quite comfortable for Black, although by no means worse for White}) 14... b4
15. Nd5 e6 16. Ne3 Ba6 17. O-O Nc5 {and Black has the initiative, L.
Ljubojevic-J.Polgar, Monte Carlo (rapid) 1995.}) (7... Nf6 8. h3 b5 9. Qd2 (9.
a3 $5 {is line 'a'}) 9... b4 10. Nd1 O-O 11. O-O {is seen via 6...Nf6 7 h3 0-0
8 Qd2 Rb8 9 Nge2 b5 10 0-0 b4 11 Nd1 in the notes to Game 19.}) 8. O-O e6 (8...
b5 9. b4 $5 e6 10. a4 a6 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rb1 Bd7 13. Na2 Ne7 14. bxc5 dxc5
15. c3 Nxe2+ 16. Qxe2 Rc8 {was J.Van der Wiel-G.Sosonko, Wijk aan Zee 1984,
and here} 17. d4 {looks somewhat better for White}) 9. Qd2 Ne7 10. Bh6 $5 (10.
Rab1 Nec6 11. a3 O-O 12. b4 {(White gets his break in first!)} cxb4 13. axb4 b5
(13... b6 {is more solid}) 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Ne2 Nxe2+ 16. Qxe2 a5 17. bxa5
Qxa5 18. Bd2 Qc7 19. Bb4 Bb7 {and while this is assessed as equal by my
computer, I definitely prefer White's position with a harmonious pawn chain, S.
Roy Chowdhury-Y.Solodovnichenko, New Delhi 2009.}) 10... Nxe2+ ({but simply} 
10... O-O 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Ne2 e5 {is about even}) 11. Nxe2 Bxb2
12. Rab1 Bf6 13. d4 $1 cxd4 14. Nxd4 a6 15. Rfd1 {gave White good compensation
for the pawn in O.Romanishin-L.Van Wely, Novy Smokovec 1992.}) 7... a6 {
This is the most consistent move and usually played, though it's not
obligatory.} ({In Chess Informant, V.Sokolov gave} 7... e6 {an exclamation
mark, following V.Hort-R.J.Fischer, Rovinj/Zagreb 1970, which continued} 8. Qd2
Nd4 9. Nf3 Ne7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bh6 e5 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Ne2 Be6
15. f4 f6 16. c3 Qa5 17. Qe1 dxc3 18. bxc3 f5 {and Black was fine.}) 8. Qd2 (8.
f4 {is also played quite frequently, when Black has several options:} Nf6 (8...
b5 9. axb5 axb5 10. e5 $5 Nd4 11. Ne4 Nh6 12. Nf3 Ng4 13. Bg1 dxe5 14. h3 Nh6
15. Nxe5 Bb7 16. c3 Ne6 17. Qd2 Ra8 18. Rd1 Rc8 19. Ng5 Bd5 20. Nxe6 Bxe6 21.
Bf2 Bd5 22. O-O {is more or less equal, R.Di Paolo-Ki.Georgiev, Italian League
2010.}) (8... Nd4 9. Nh3 Nf6 10. Nf2 e5 11. fxe5 dxe5 12. Nd5 Be6 $6 ({Black
should prefer} 12... Nxd5 13. exd5 b6 14. O-O Bb7 15. c4 O-O {with equal
chances}) 13. c3 Bxd5 14. exd5 Nf5 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qf3 O-O 18. O-O
{and White is in the driver's seat, I.Starostits-V.Zavoronkov, Tallinn (rapid)
2005.}) 9. h3 O-O 10. Nf3 Qb6 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. O-O b5 13. axb5 axb5 14. g4 b4
15. Ne2 e6 16. Qe1 Re8 17. Qh4 Ne7 18. Ng3 ({or} 18. Nd2 Bb7) {. EXERCISE:
White is building up to throw either g4-g5, f4-f5, or both at Black.  How
should he respond to these threats? ANSWER:} 18... g5 $3 {(ouch!! – it turns
out that White's queen is trapped)} 19. fxg5 ({or} 19. Qxg5 h6 20. Qh4 Ng6)
19... Ng6 20. gxf6 Nxh4 21. Nxh4 (21. fxg7 Nxf3+ 22. Rxf3 Kxg7 23. Rbf1 {
offers a few more chances}) 21... Bf8 {and White is obviously lost, M.Gähler-T.
Burg, Zürich 2010.}) 8... e6 {This position could also arrive via 6...e6 7 Qd2
Rb8 8 a4 a6. There is nothing at all wrong with 8...e6 here, even if advancing
the b-pawn seems more consistent, given that Black has spent two moves
preparing it.} ({After} 8... b5 9. axb5 axb5 {, White has tried:} 10. Nge2 (10.
f4 b4 11. Nd1 e6 12. Nf3 Nge7 13. O-O O-O {transposes to the 9...e6 line in
the notes to the next game.}) (10. Rb1 {(consolidating the queenside at the
cost of giving up the a-file)} b4 11. Nd1 Nd4 12. b3 Nf6 13. h3 O-O 14. Ne2 e5
15. Nxd4 cxd4 16. Bg5 d5 17. exd5 Bb7 18. O-O Bxd5 19. f4 $6 (19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20.
Bxd5 Qd6 21. Nb2 {is level}) 19... Bxg2 20. Qxg2 exf4 21. Bxf4 {and a draw was
agreed in M.Simons-B.Lalic, British League 2005, although Black's position
looks somewhat preferable after} Rc8 {in view of his safer king position,
along with White's backward c-pawn and holes at c3 and e3.}) 10... b4 11. Nd1
Nd4 12. O-O e6 ({or} 12... e5 13. Nc1 Ne7 14. c3 bxc3 15. bxc3 Ne6 16. Bh6 O-O
17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Ne3 f5 19. exf5 gxf5 20. f4 exf4 21. gxf4 d5 {with an
unclear position, M.Ivanov-Ma.Andersen, World Junior Championship, Caldas
Novas 2011}) 13. Nc1 Qb6 (13... Ne7 {transposes to the 10...e6 line in the
notes to Game 16}) 14. c3 Nc6 15. f4 Nge7 16. Qf2 bxc3 17. bxc3 O-O 18. Ra2 Bd7
19. g4 f5 20. gxf5 exf5 21. e5 dxe5 22. Bxc5 Qc7 {and both sides have their
chances, C.Bank Friis-L.Schandorff, Danish Championship, Holstebro 1987.}) 9.
Nge2 Nd4 10. Nd1 {This looks like a thematic retreat, clearing the way for
c2-c3, but in fact White has an unusual idea in mind.} ({A more standard path
is} 10. O-O Ne7 ({here} 10... b5 {might be met by} 11. axb5 axb5 12. b4 $5 {
, intending} Nxe2+ 13. Nxe2 Bxa1 14. Rxa1 {with strong play on the dark
squares for the exchange}) 11. Nd1 (11. Bh6 $5 O-O ({both} 11... Bxh6 12. Qxh6
Nxc2 13. Rac1 Nb4 14. d4) ({and} 11... Nxe2+ 12. Nxe2 Bxb2 13. Rab1 Bf6 14. d4
{give White reasonable compensation for the pawn}) 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. f4 Nec6
14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. e5 d5 16. g4 Qh4 17. h3 Bd7 18. Ne2 Nxe2+ 19. Qxe2 a5 20. Kh2
b6 {with chances for both sides, V.Gorkavij-I.Kudelya, Taganrog 2014.}) 11...
O-O ({or} 11... b5 {again}) 12. Nc1 f5 13. c3 Ndc6 14. Bh6 Bxh6 15. Qxh6 e5 16.
Ne2 Be6 17. Ne3 Kh8 18. Nd5 Ng8 19. Qd2 Bxd5 20. exd5 Na5 21. Qc2 f4 22. Bh3 b6
23. f3 fxg3 24. hxg3 {with an unusual but roughly equal position, M.Zlatic-N.
Djukic, Serbian League 2004.}) 10... Ne7 ({Black can still advance the b-pawn
if desired; indeed,} 10... b5 11. axb5 axb5 12. O-O b4 {transposes to 8...b5
lines above.}) 11. Nxd4 $5 {White suddenly takes the game in a different
direction.} ({As we saw in the previous note,} 11. Nc1 {, followed by c2-c3,
is the usual idea behind Nd1, though it offers White no particular advantage.})
11... cxd4 12. Bh6 O-O 13. h4 {Launching a kingside attack.} (13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14.
O-O Qc7 {does not rock the boat and leaves the game more or less balanced.})
13... Bxh6 {QUESTION: Should Black not delay this move until White has made a
decision about castling or not? Is seems a little hazardous to invite the
white queen to h6 at this point. ANSWER: While it certainly would look safer
to wait until White has castled, who knows if White would accommodate Black
with that favour? Anyway, in this case it is actually perfectly safe, since
there is no imminent danger of Black getting mated.} 14. Qxh6 Kh8 ({As we have
already seen,} 14... f6 {is pretty much the standard reply against a queen on
h6 and an oncoming h-pawn. White has to respond with} 15. Qd2 {if he intends
to push the h-pawn forward} ({as usual} 15. h5 $4 {loses to} g5 {, intending ..
.Kh8 and ...Ng8}) {, after which} 15... Nc6 16. f4 Bd7 {is about even.}) ({
Alternatively,} 14... Nc6 15. h5 Qe7 {defends for the time being, but White
might then increase the pressure with} 16. f4 {, followed by Nf2-h3-g5, while
the black f-pawn is stuck supporting its colleague on g6.}) 15. h5 Ng8 16. Qd2
g5 17. c3 e5 {When I first went through this game, I thought Black's last two
pawn moves were somewhat unnecessary, but looking again now it appears to be a
perfectly viable option.} 18. cxd4 exd4 19. f4 ({Or} 19. O-O Qf6 20. b4 Be6 {
with about even chances.}) 19... gxf4 20. Qxf4 ({Here} 20. gxf4 {is possibly
safer, but Black has no serious problems in this line; e.g.} Bd7 21. Nf2 Rc8 {
with chances for both sides.}) 20... f5 $2 {This attempt to exploit the
position of White's king and queen is easily answered.} (20... Qa5+ 21. Ke2 Qe5
{was a better choice, when Black has a rather pleasant game.}) 21. O-O $1 {
Evacuating the king from the centre as well as pinning the black f-pawn.} Qf6
$6 ({It is difficult to look into the future, but it would probably have been
better to put the queen on e7; for example,} 21... Qe7 22. Nf2 ({or} 22. Rc1
Nf6 23. exf5 Qe5 24. Rc7 Rg8) 22... fxe4 23. Qxe4 Qg7 24. Qh4 Nh6 25. Ne4 Bf5
26. Rae1 ({or} 26. Nxd6 Bxd3) 26... Bxe4 27. Rxf8+ Rxf8 28. Rxe4 Nf5 29. Qg4 b6
{and White has the better chances, but Black is still alive.}) 22. Nf2 Qe5 ({Or
} 22... Bd7 23. exf5 Bxf5 24. Ne4 Bxe4 25. Qxe4 Qg7 26. Rae1 {, when in
comparison with the previous note, the exchange of minor pieces favours White.}
) 23. Qxe5+ dxe5 24. Ng4 Be6 25. Nxe5 ({Another option is} 25. exf5 Rxf5 26.
Rxf5 Bxf5 27. Nxe5 Nh6 28. Rc1 {and White has an extra pawn and the clearly
better chances.}) 25... fxe4 $6 {This only helps White further.} (25... Nh6 {
offers more resistance.}) 26. Rxf8 Rxf8 27. Bxe4 ({Here Black decided to
resign, which seems a bit early, but continuing would have been on a one-way
street; e.g.} 27. Bxe4 b6 28. a5 bxa5 29. Rxa5 Bc8 30. Nc6 Nf6 31. Bf3 Bb7 32.
Nxd4 Bxf3 33. Nxf3 Nxh5 34. Kg2 Nf6 35. Rxa6 {and now with two extra pawns,
White should win easily enough.}) 1-0

