1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Rb8 7. Qd2 b5 {There
is little point in Black delaying this advance;} ({but it's worth noting that
the position after} 7... e6 {can also be reached via 6...e6 7 Qd2 Rb8. As we
said in Chapter One, this will generally transpose to 7...b5 lines where Black
plays a later ...e7-e6. For example:} 8. Nge2 (8. a4 a6 {returns to the
previous game.}) (8. f4 b5 9. Nf3 b4 10. Nd1 {is the note with 9...e6 below.})
(8. Nf3 b5 9. O-O b4 10. Nd1 {is 9...e6 in the notes to Game 15.} (10. Z0))
8... Nd4 (8... b5 9. O-O b4 10. Nd1 Nd4 {is 10...e6 in the notes to Game 16})
9. O-O {, and now} b5 {is 9...e6 in the notes to the same game;} ({while} 9...
Ne7 {(without ...b7-b5) was seen via 7 Nge2 Nd4 in the notes to Game 13.})) ({
Otherwise, for what it's worth,} 7... e5 {was seen in the notes to Game 8;}) ({
while} 7... Nf6 8. h3 {features in the notes to Game 22.}) 8. f4 {This
position perhaps belongs in Chapter Nine (via 6 f4 Rb8), but it's more often
reached via the game move order so we'll examine it here.} ({Of White's
alternatives:} 8. Nf3 {is considered in the next game;}) ({and} 8. Nge2 {
in Games 16-17.}) ({Instead,} 8. Nd1 b4 {merely switches the move order;}) ({
while} 8. a3 a5 {, followed by 9...b4 10 axb4 axb4, comes to the same thing as
7 a4 a6, followed by 8...b5 9 axb5 axb5 and 10...b4, in the notes to the
previous game.}) 8... b4 9. Nd1 Qb6 {QUESTION: I'm not sure I understand why
placing the queen opposite the white bishop on e3 is a good idea. ANSWER:
Kramnik is quite fond of this move, which increases Black's control over the
important d4-square and allows some additional options in terms of completing
his development, as we will see in this game. The fact that the queen is
"facing" the bishop is only a minor nuisance.} ({Naturally, Black has numerous
other possibilities: a)} 9... e5 10. Nf3 exf4 11. Bxf4 Bg4 12. O-O Nge7 13. c3
bxc3 14. bxc3 O-O 15. Ne3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Ne5 17. Bg2 {and White's position is
favourable, O.Castro Rojas-J.Dorfman, Oviedo (rapid) 1991.}) ({b)} 9... Bg4 10.
Nf3 e6 11. O-O Nge7 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qc7 14. Bg2 O-O 15. c3 bxc3 16. bxc3
f5 17. Rc1 Kh8 18. exf5 gxf5 $6 (18... Nxf5 19. Bf2 {is still marginally
better for White, but is definitely to be preferred over the game continuation}
) 19. Bf2 Ng6 20. d4 {and White is clearly in command of the game, A.
Krapivin-E.Miroshnichenko, Russian Team Championship 2007.}) ({c)} 9... Ba6 10.
Ne2 e6 11. O-O Nf6 12. Nf2 O-O 13. a3 {(trying to exploit the bishop's
unguarded placement on a6)} Bb7 $6 {(Black panics a bit)} ({instead,} 13... b3
$5 14. c3 Qb6 {is perfectly acceptable – in fact my computer assesses it as
good for Black, which may be a bit of a stretch}) 14. axb4 cxb4 15. c4 bxc3 16.
bxc3 Nd7 17. Bxa7 Nxa7 18. Rxa7 Qb6 19. Ra2 Ba8 20. d4 {and White was up a
pawn which he converted in a long game, N.Short-A.Greenfeld, Douglas 2014.}) ({
d)} 9... e6 10. Nf3 Nge7 11. O-O {and now:} O-O (11... Nd4 12. Nh4 $5 (12. c3
bxc3 13. bxc3 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 O-O 15. d4 {sets Black few problems; e.g.} Ba6 16.
Re1 cxd4 17. cxd4 d5 18. e5 Nf5 19. Bf2 Qb6 20. Be2 Bxe2 21. Rxe2 h5 22. h3
Rfc8 23. g4 hxg4 24. hxg4 Ne7 25. Be3 Qb4 {and I prefer Black's position, P.
Vieira-S.Dumont, Vitoria 2001}) 12... f5 13. c3 bxc3 14. bxc3 Ndc6 15. exf5
gxf5 16. Nf3 Nd5 17. Re1 O-O 18. Bf2 Bd7 19. Rc1 h6 20. h3 Qa5 21. d4 Nf6 22.
Ne5 $1 dxe5 23. dxe5 Rfd8 24. exf6 Bxf6 {was A.Krapivin-J.Gunnarsson, Budapest
2003, and here} 25. Ne3 $1 {, intending Nc4, looks somewhat better for White.})
12. a3 a5 13. axb4 axb4 14. d4 ({or} 14. Rb1 Ba6 15. b3 Nd4 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17.
Bf2 Qc7 18. Ra1 Bb5 19. Ra2 f5 20. exf5 Nxf5 21. g4 Ne7 22. Re1 Bd7 {with a
dynamic position where both sides have their share of the chances, A.
Krapivin-I.Khairullin, St Petersburg 2009, although my preference would be
