unprotected. ANSWER: You would certainly think so. I did a double take when I
first saw this move. Of course Miles did experiment quite a bit in the opening,
but he rarely played moves that got him in a clearly worse position from the
outset.} ({Black has occasionally prepared ...b7-b5 with} 6... a6 {as well,
but that doesn't seem part of a coherent plan; e.g.} 7. Qd2 b5 8. f4 Bb7 9. Nf3
Nf6 10. h3 e6 (10... O-O 11. O-O b4 12. Nd1 a5 {is more thematic}) 11. O-O h5
$2 {, A.Csaba-T.Sleisz, Budapest 1995, and now} 12. e5 $1 dxe5 13. fxe5 Nd7 14.
Ne4 {would have been very good for White.}) ({If Black simply wants to develop,
it's possible to advance the b-pawn a single square:} 6... b6 7. Qd2 ({for} 7.
f4 {see the notes to Game 51 in Chapter Nine}) 7... Bb7 8. Nh3 ({White has
tried putting the knight on its other squares too:} 8. Nge2 Qd7 9. O-O Nd4 10.
Nd1 e6 11. Nc1 Nf6 12. c3 Nc6 13. Bh6 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 Qe7 15. Ne2 O-O-O 16. Qc1
d5 {and Black is not worse, A.Vella Ramirez-B.Damljanovic, Lorca 2001}) ({or} 
8. Nf3 Qd7 9. O-O Nd4 10. Nh4 e6 11. Nd1 Ne7 12. c3 Ndc6 13. d4 cxd4 14. cxd4
O-O 15. Nc3 d5 {with chances for both sides, E.Kovalevskaya-T.Kosintseva,
Krasnoturinsk 2005}) 8... Nf6 9. Bh6 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 e6 11. O-O-O Qe7 12. Rhe1
O-O-O 13. Qd2 h5 14. f3 h4 15. g4 Nd4 16. g5 Nh5 17. f4 Kb8 {with a quite
obscure position, J.Hjartarson-H.Olafsson, Reykjavik 1992.}) 7. e5 {The
critical response;} (7. Nxb5 $6 Rb8 {is just bad for White.}) ({Otherwise
Black will just advance ...b5-b4, though White can always allow this and play
for a2-a3. For example,} 7. Qd2 b4 8. Nd1 e5 $5 (8... a5) ({or indeed} 8... Rb8
