1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Nh6 $5 {QUESTION: This
seems very odd. It doesn't look like the knight has much of a future on h6,
and can't White just attack it with h2-h3 and Qd2 - ? ANSWER: It does indeed
look a bit unusual, but the h6-square is only a temporary stop; and while
White certainly can play the moves you mention, Black has something in mind
for the knight.} ({Regarding which, Black has a not too dissimilar idea in} 
6... f5 {and then:} 7. exf5 (7. Qd2 fxe4 8. dxe4 (8. Bxe4 $6 Nf6 9. Bh6 O-O 10.
Bxg7 Kxg7 11. Bg2 e5 12. h4 h6 13. Ne4 Bg4 14. c3 Qe7 {is quite pleasant for
Black, J.Moreno Carnero-P.Glavina Rossi, Linares 1997}) 8... Ne5 9. f4 Nc4 10.
Qd3 Nxe3 11. Qxe3 Nh6 12. Nge2 O-O 13. h3 b5 14. g4 b4 15. Nd1 Bb7 16. O-O Nf7
{and Black has the better chances, M.Loeffler-F.Ochoa de Echaguen, French
League 1998.}) 7... Bxf5 8. Nge2 Nf6 9. h3 e5 10. Qd2 Qd7 11. g4 Be6 12. f4 O-O
{was agreed drawn in M.Narciso Dublan-D.Garcia Ilundain, Barcelona 1998, but
there is obviously still plenty left to play for. One possibly continuation is}
13. fxe5 Nxe5 14. Nf4 Rae8 15. O-O-O {with a position I think is more pleasant
for White, though that could be a matter of taste.}) 7. h3 ({There is no
reason to allow – or force – the knight to jump to g4 after} 7. Qc1 $5 {
, though this was the choice of both Smyslov and Pachman in a couple of early
games against Bronstein. See the transposition 6...Nf6 7 Qc1!? Ng4 in the
notes to Game 18.}) 7... f5 {This is Black's idea, clearing a retreat square
for the knight, while at the same time attacking the white centre.} 8. Qd2 Nf7
9. Nge2 ({The main alternative is} 9. f4 {, after which the game can turn very
sharp and messy; for example,} O-O 10. Nf3 Rb8 11. h4 ({or} 11. O-O e6 12. d4
fxe4 13. Nxe4 b6 14. Rad1 d5 15. Nf2 Nd6 16. c3 {is roughly equal, L.Yudasin-H.
Nakamura, New York rapid 2002}) 11... Qb6 12. Rb1 Nh6 {(back again)} 13. h5 Ng4
14. Bg1 Bd7 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Ng5 e6 17. exf5 gxf5 18. Nd5 Qd8 {with chances
for both sides, V.Samolins-I.Starostits, Cambados 2007.}) 9... O-O ({Black can
also play} 9... Nd4 {straight away, when 10 f4 0-0 transposes to the next note,
but} 10. h4 {might instead be met by} fxe4 11. dxe4 ({or} 11. Bxe4 Bg4) 11...
Nxe2 12. Qxe2 Bxc3+ $5 13. bxc3 Qa5 14. O-O Ne5 {and if} 15. f4 {then} Bg4 {
with an unclear position.}) 10. h4 ({This is far more enterprising than} 10. f4
Nd4 ({or} 10... Bd7 11. O-O Nd4 12. Nd1 Rb8 13. c3 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 e6 15. Nf2 b5
{, which is approximately even, D.De Vreugt-Y.Pelletier, Zug 2001}) 11. O-O e6
12. Nd1 Qc7 13. Kh2 Bd7 14. Ng1 Rae8 15. c3 Nc6 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Nf3 Ne7 {
with mutual chances, A.Skripchenko-N.Benmesbah, French Women's Championship,
Saint Quentin 2015.}) 10... Nd4 11. h5 Nxe2 $6 {With the pressure building
against his kingside, Black feels the need remove the white knight before it
can appear at f4, but it fails to solve his problems entirely.} ({The computer
prefers} 11... fxe4 $5 {, and then} 12. hxg6 hxg6 13. dxe4 ({or} 13. Nxe4 Nxe2
14. Qxe2 Bxb2 15. Rb1 Bg7) ({or} 13. Bxe4 Bg4 $1 {, though such lines perhaps
require nerves of silicon}) ({and White might try} 13. O-O-O $5 {as well})
13... Nxe2 14. Qxe2 Ne5 {.}) 12. Qxe2 e6 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. exf5 exf5 {QUESTION:
How should this position be evaluated? On the surface it appears that Black
has more weaknesses than White: the open h-file, the g6-pawn, the d5-square,
and so on. Is that a fair assessment? ANSWER: Absolutely; you are hitting on
all the sore points in Black's position. Although none of them are easy to
exploit at the moment, they certainly do contribute to the overall evaluation.}
15. Nd5 $6 {Very aggressive, quite possibly overly so.} ({After the more
mundane} 15. Qd2 Re8 16. O-O-O Qa5 17. d4 {, White should have a comfortable
advantage.}) 15... Bxb2 16. Rb1 Bg7 $2 ({With} 16... Be5 {Black can keep the
balance. Now things go a little crazy.}) 17. Bxc5 $2 {With the idea of 17...
dxc5?? 18 Ne7+ and wins, but Black does not have to take the bishop.} ({
Therefore White should have played} 17. Nf4 {, and if Black guards the g-pawn
with} Qf6 (17... g5 $4 18. Qh5 {wins at once}) {, only then} 18. Bxc5 $1 {
, since} dxc5 $2 ({while} 18... Qc3+ 19. Kf1 Qxc5 20. Nxg6 {(threatening Ne7
mate)} Ne5 21. Bd5+ $1 Rf7 22. Nf4 {also wins for White}) 19. Nd5 {is just as
bad.}) {EXERCISE: Whether the bishop is taken or not, White is still
threatening Ne7+ etc. How should Black deal with this? ANSWER:} 17... Be6 $1 {
A clever resource.} ({If now} 17... Be6 18. Qxe6 ({while retreating with} 18.
Be3 {drops a piece to} Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Qa5+ {etc}) {, then} 18... Re8 {pins the
queen to the king.}) 18. Qxe6 $5 {White takes the bishop anyway!} ({There is
nothing better;} 18. Nf4 Bxa2 19. Rxb7 dxc5 20. Nxg6 Re8 21. Ne7+ Kf8 22. Ng6+
Kg8 23. Ne7+ {leads to a draw by repetition.}) 18... Re8 19. Qxe8+ Qxe8+ 20.
Be3 Rb8 21. Kf1 b6 {Despite White having only rook and bishop for the queen,
chances are more or less even, due to his well-placed forces: rooks on open
files and minor pieces on active squares.} 22. g4 $5 {White takes a bit of a
gamble, wanting to crack open Black's kingside.} Qa4 $6 {Black is a little too
willing to settle for a draw, in which his opponent is clearly not interested,
given his previous move.} ({Instead,} 22... fxg4 23. Rb4 Qd7 24. Rc4 (24. Be4
g5 25. Bf5 Qb7 $1 26. Be4 Qd7 {is another possible draw}) 24... Rb7 {leads to
a complex position where both sides have their share of the chances}) 23. Ne7+
Kf8 24. Nxg6+ Kg8 25. Ne7+ Kf8 26. Ng6+ Kg8 27. Ne7+ Kf8 {White repeats moves
in order to gain time on the clock and bring the time control a little closer.}
28. Nxf5 Qxc2 ({Not} 28... Ne5 $6 {since the removal of Black's dark-squared
bishop after} 29. Bh6 $1 Bxh6 30. Rxh6 {leaves him in difficulties; e.g.} Qxc2
31. Rf6+ Nf7 32. Re1 Qxd3+ 33. Kg1 Qc3 34. Ree6 Re8 ({or} 34... Rd8 35. Bd5)
35. Rxd6 Qa1+ 36. Kh2 Qe5+ 37. Kh3 Qc3+ 38. Kh4 Qe5 39. f4 $1 Qxf4 ({or} 39...
Qb2 40. Nh6 Re7 41. g5 {etc}) 40. Rxf7+ $1 Kxf7 41. Bd5+ {and White wins.}) 29.
Rc1 Qxd3+ 30. Kg1 Ne5 $4 ({Instead, Black should have played} 30... Qe2 {
, when a possible continuation is} 31. Rh4 Bf6 32. g5 Nxg5 33. Bxg5 Bxg5 34.
Rh8+ Kf7 35. Rc7+ Kg6 36. Rxb8 Qd1+ 37. Kh2 Kxf5 {with a position neither side
should be able to win.}) {EXERCISE: Black's last move, which looks completely
logical and good, turns out to be a blunder, which you now know because I told
you. With that information in hand, can you determine White's winning move? 
(Warning: it is not easy to spot, though White did find it in the game.)
ANSWER:} 31. Rh3 $3 {Why is this move so good? First of all, it threatens to
win material with 32 Nxg7, which cannot be recaptured due to 33 Bh6+ with a
discovered attack on the queen. But most of all it demonstrates that Black's
pieces, despite looking active and reasonably coordinated, are in fact
anything but that. The king is vulnerable, the queen is loose, and the rook is
unprotected too.} Qe2 ({The magnitude of Black's problems is well illustrated
by the sequence} 31... Nxg4 32. Nxg7 Nxe3 33. Rc7 Qd1+ 34. Kh2 {, when Black
will either get mated or fall decisively behind in material.}) 32. Nxg7 Kxg7
33. Rc7+ Nf7 ({If Black moves the king, we see how well everything works out
for White tactically:} 33... Kf6 34. Rh6+ Ng6 35. g5+ Ke5 36. Rxg6 Qd1+ 37. Kh2
Qh5+ {(it seems like Black just turned things around, but not so fast...)} 38.
Kg3 Qxg6 39. Re7+ {(ouch, the king has no escape squares)} Qe6 40. f4+ Kf5 41.
Bh3+ Ke4 42. Rxe6+ {and White is winning easily;}) ({or just} 33... Kg8 $2 34.
Bd5+ {.}) 34. Bf3 {Several moves win for White at this juncture, but Feller
has a specific target in mind and this works perfectly.} Qxa2 {EXERCISE: How
should White continue? ANSWER:} 35. Rh5 $1 {Targeting the knight on f7 and
Black's open king. The immediate threat is 36 Bd5.} Re8 36. Bd5 Qb1+ 37. Kg2
Rxe3 {Black is running out of moves and counterplay.} ({The knight cannot be
protected any longer; e.g.} 37... Rf8 38. Bh6+) ({and} 37... Qg6 38. Rg5 {
both win a bucketload of material.}) 38. Rxf7+ Kg6 39. fxe3 Qd1 40. Rf3 {
With White having reached the time control, Black's only hope is for a
perpetual check, but that is not likely to happen. In fact, according to my
silicon friend, Black's king is actually getting mated by force!} Qc2+ 41. Kg3
({It doesn't really matter but} 41. Kh3 $1 {is more precise, after which Black
doesn't even have any checks; e.g.} Qb1 ({or} 41... Qc1 42. Be4+ Kg7 43. Rg5+ {
and mates}) 42. Rf8 {(note that both f1 and h1 are covered)} Qg1 ({or} 42...
Qd3 43. Kh4 $1) 43. Rg8+ Kf6 44. Rf5+ Ke7 45. Rf7# {.}) 41... Qb1 42. Rh1 $5 {
An entirely practical continuation: if Black takes the rook then 43 Rf6+ and
44 Bxh1 removes even the slightest chances of a draw.} Qd3 43. Be6 ({Or} 43.
Bf7+ Kg7 44. g5 d5 45. g6 Kf8 46. Rh8+ Ke7 47. g7 {and it is all over.}) 43...
Qc3 44. Bf5+ Kf6 45. Rh6+ Ke7 46. Rh7+ Kf6 47. Be4+ Ke6 48. Bd5+ Ke5 ({But} 
48... Kxd5 49. e4+ {is hardly any better.}) 49. Rh5# 1-0

