} 12... Nf5 $1 {here}) 13. Nxe5 {transposes to 13 Qf2 in the main game.}) 12...
Bd7 13. Nd2 Qa4 14. c3 Nc2 15. Rc1 Nxe3 16. Nxe3 {was V.Ronin-A.Kabatianski,
Russian Team Championship 1989, and here} Qa6 17. Nec4 Ne7 18. a4 Rad8 {
looks like the best way to equalize.}) ({c)} 11. Nh4 f5 $5 {(Black takes the
threat of f4-f5 very seriously and hurries to blockade it)} ({although} 11...
O-O {should be fine}) 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Qf2 Bd7 14. Rfc1 b5 ({instead,} 14...
Bf6 15. a3 Bxh4 16. b4 Qc7 17. gxh4 Rg8 {looks quite pleasant for Black}) ({
who might even consider} 14... O-O-O $5) 15. Nd1 b4 16. c3 bxc3 17. bxc3 Nb5
18. Bd2 Qa6 19. Bf1 Na3 20. d4 c4 21. d5 {(now Black has to be very careful
because the king is fending for himself and his pieces are not particularly
well coordinated)} exd5 22. Qe2+ Kf8 23. Qh5 Ne7 24. Bh3 Be8 $6 (24... d4 $1 {
is better, creating some active counterplay and allow connection between the
two wings}) 25. Qf3 Bg6 26. Ne3 Qc8 27. Kh1 Bf6 $6 28. Nxd5 Bxh4 29. Bg2 Qc6 $4
(29... Rb8 30. gxh4 {is good for White, but the text loses at once}) 30. Nxe7
Qxf3 31. Nxg6+ hxg6 32. Bxf3 Bxg3 33. Kg2 $1 {1-0 A.Strikovic-V.Gallego
