6. d3 h5 7. h3 e5 8. Be3 Nge7 9. Qd2 {.}) 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3
h5 $5 {This provocative thrust was endorsed by John Emms in 'Dangerous Weapons:
Anti-Sicilians'. QUESTION: What's the purpose behind this move? Is Black
starting a kingside attack before White has castled? ANSWER: Well, if White
castles kingside and furthermore is a bit careless then, yes, Black can get a
kingside attack going, but that's not the real point of the move. QUESTION: So
what is the point then? ANSWER: Since the standard plan with Bh6 has at least
temporarily – perhaps permanently – been prevented, it is reasonable to
expect White to play f2-f4 instead, and that's when the idea behind ...h7-h5
comes into play: Black can follow up with ...h5-h4 and attack White on the
dark squares. This usually involves inserting ...e7-e5 as well. QUESTION: So
should White play h2-h4 to prevent Black's plan? ANSWER: Preferably not, since
it weakens the g4-square, especially if White follows up with a later f2-f4.}
7. h3 ({There are various other options to consider: a)} 7. h4 $6 {is met by}
Nf6 {, heading straight for g4; e.g.} 8. Nh3 ({or} 8. f3 d5 $1 9. Bxc5 d4 $1
10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Qxd5 12. Ba3 Bh6 {and Black is clearly better, R.
