17... Bc7 18. Rad1 b6 {, J.Furhoff-T.Hellborg, Swedish League 2002, then} 19.
Bd6 $1 Bxd6 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. Qxa8 Ne3 22. Qxa7 {will leave White a pawn up})
18. Rad1 Bd7 19. Nd6 Bc6 20. d5 $1 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 exd5 22. Nxf5 gxf5 23. Qxf5
Qc7 24. Bd4 Bxd4+ 25. cxd4 {and White has a strong attack, J.Claesen-A.
Dgebuadze, World Student Team Championship, Leon 1996.}) ({d)} 10... f5 {
is typically a move Black needs to be careful playing, even if it is often
seen in the Closed Sicilian. Here it risks weakening Black's control of the
dark squares; e.g.} 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. Ne5 Rb8 ({after} 12... Bxe5 13. fxe5 Qxe5
14. Bf4 {, White has good compensation for the pawn}) 13. a4 a5 14. Nc4 Qd8 15.
Nb1 Nd5 16. Bd2 b6 17. Nba3 Bb7 18. c3 Nc6 19. Qb3 {and White has a nice
dynamic plus, I.Starostits-M.Ivanov, Leutersdorf 2001.}) ({e)} 10... dxe5 {
