1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. f4 ({Short actually played
} 6. Nh3 {first. We will look at this move more closely in Chapter Ten.}) 6...
e5 7. Nh3 {Deploying the knight to the edge is usually considered optimal in
this set-up. From h3 it is able to go either to g5 or f4 (should Black play ...
e5xf4), it obstructs neither the f1-rook (after White castles) nor the queen 
(in the case of f4-f5 and ...g6xf5), and it cannot be swapped off with ...Nd4.}
({The more 'natural'} 7. Nf3 {is examined in Games 41-43;}) ({while} 7. Nge2 {
appears via 6 Nge2 e5 in Chapter Ten.}) 7... Nge7 {The usual reply.} ({We will
look at the aggressive alternative} 7... h5 $5 {in Game 40.}) ({Black does
have another significant option in} 7... exf4 $5 {. It seems contrary to
Black's best interests to give up the central pawn so readily, while allowing
White either to develop the c1-bishop to f4 in one go (without making a stop
on e3) or bring the h3-knight across to participate in the battle for the
centre, but 7...exf4 has been tried by some rather strong players and does
have two points in its favour.} {Instead,} 8. Nxf4 ({Black gains the e5-square
as an outpost (} 8. gxf4 $4 {loses a piece to} Bxh3 9. Bxh3 Qh4+ {) and White
is no longer able to play f4-f5.}) ({For example:} 8. Bxf4 Nge7 9. O-O h6 {
(to preserve the g7-bishop)} (9... O-O 10. Qd2 Rb8 11. Bh6 b5 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13.
Nf4 b4 14. Ncd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Ne7 16. Nf6 {perhaps offers White a little
something, P.Garcia Castro-U.Andersson, EU Championship, Liverpool 2008}) 10.
Rb1 ({if White tries to prevent ...0-0 by playing} 10. Qd2 {, Black has no
problem opting for} g5 11. Be3 O-O 12. Qd1 Ne5 13. Nf2 f5 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Nd5
Be6 16. c3 Qd7 {with a pleasant game, J.Landaw-E.Sevillano, Monterey Park 2013}
) 10... O-O 11. a3 Be6 12. Be3 Ne5 13. Nf4 Bd7 14. Kh1 Rc8 15. Qd2 Kh7 16. h3
Bc6 17. g4 {and White is at most a smidgen better, B.Spassky-L.Portisch,
Geneva (13th matchgame) 1977.}) 8... Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 {transposes to 9..
.exf4 10 Nxf4 in the notes to Game 6,} ({while} 10. Nfd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Be6 12.
Nf4 Bd7 13. c3 b5 14. a3 a5 15. Be3 Ne5 16. h3 a4 {leaves Black with the
better chances, I.Bilek-L.Evans, Lugano Olympiad 1968.})) 8. O-O ({White can
also play} 8. f5 $5 {at once:} {Instead,} O-O (8... gxf5 9. Qh5 Nd4 $2 {
allowing the white knight to g5 is very risky;} ({similarly} 9... O-O 10. Ng5
$1 h6 11. Nf3) ({so Black should prefer} 9... h6 {, when} 10. O-O Nd4 {
transposes to Game 39}) 10. Ng5 Rf8 11. Qxh7 Bf6 ({or} 11... Nxc2+ $2 12. Kd1
Nxa1 13. Qxg7 Kd7 14. Nh7 Rh8 15. Bg5 {1-0 I.Starostits-E.Jakubiec, Krakow 2010
}) 12. O-O Ne6 13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. exf5 $1 Rh8 15. Ne4 Nxf5 16. Rxf5 Rxh7 17.
Nxf6+ Kf8 18. Nxh7+ Kg7 19. Rh5 {and White has far too much for the queen, H.
Pecorelli Garcia-G.Estevez Morales, Cienfuegos 1991.}) 9. O-O {transposes to
our main game;} ({but} 9. g4 $5 {comes into consideration here.})) 8... O-O {
This looks the normal move, but it actually dares White to come forward with a
big stick.} ({We will look at} 8... Nd4 {in Game 39.}) ({Alternatively: a)} 
8... exf4 $5 {is again possible, when 9 Bxf4 and 9 Nxf4 return to the previous
note, but in this case Black has to reckon} 9. gxf4 {as well; for example,} f5
